May 2024

Structural Bayesian Techniques for Experimental and Behavioral Economics

Introduction

Answering research questions with structural econometrics

I have a model, and I want to …

  • Estimate the parameters in the model
  • Compute economically meaningfully quantities from the parameters in my model
  • Quantify how much heterogeneity is present between participants in my model’s parameters
  • Use my model to make a prediction about behavior in another setting

But you should also quantify the uncertainty you have in all of these

Estimating parameters in a model

My model says that parameter(s) are important, so I want to know what they are.

For example, some preference models

\[ \begin{aligned} \text{Risk: }& U(L) = E\left(\frac{X^{1-r}}{1-r}\mid L\right) \\ \text{Time: }& U(x) = \sum_{t=0}^{\infty} \delta^t x_t\\ \text{Other-regarding: }& U_i(x)=x_i-\frac{\alpha}{n-1}\sum_{j\neq i}\max\left\{x_j-x_i,0\right\}\\ &\quad\quad \quad\quad-\frac{\beta}{n-1}\sum_{j\neq i}\max\left\{x_i-x_j,0\right\} \end{aligned} \]

Computing economically meaningful quantities

What I really want to do is interpret a transformation of the parameters.

E.g. a certainty equivalent:

\[ \begin{aligned} U(L)&= E\left(\frac{X^{1-r}}{1-r}\mid L\right)\\ \\ & C(L)\sim L\\ C(L)&= \left[E\left(X^{1-r}\mid L\right)\right]^\frac{1}{1-r} \end{aligned} \]

\(C(L)\) converts expected utility units (hard to interpret and compare) into dollars

Quantifying heterogeneity

Parameter \(\theta\) is likely not the same for every participant

Assume (for example):

\[ \theta_i\sim iid N(\mu,\sigma^2) \]

Estimate and interpret \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\)

Making predictions

Parameters \(\theta\) imply something about choices \(y\) in scenario \(S\):

\[ p(y\mid\theta,S) \]

  • For the same participant in another scenario
    • Model evaluation
  • For different participants in similar scenarios
    • Scaling an experiment up from a pilot
  • For different participants in a new scenario
    • Designing a new experiment

Answering research questions with structural econometrics – more

I have more than one model, and I want to …

  • Classify participants into one model
  • Determine which model best organizes the data
  • Determine what fraction of participants behave according to each model
  • Use these models to make a prediction about behavior in another setting

Classifying participants and data

Two models \(M_1\) and \(M_2\) imply different things about choices:

  • Bracket decisions narrowly or broadly?
  • CRRA or CARA utility functions?
  • Exponential or hyperbolic discounting?
  • Quantal response equilibrium or a learning model?

Which model seems to be the better model for a participant’s data?

Which model seems to be the better model for the data overall?

But both (all) models could be important

Each participant could use either \(M_1\) or \(M_2\)

Participants could sometimes use \(M_1\) and sometimes use \(M_2\)

Making predictions with more than one model

A combination of \(M_1\) and \(M_2\) could do better than any one on its own

What could these models look like?

A utility function our participants could be maximizing

  • E.g. risk preferences

An equilibrium concept in a game

  • E.g. Quantal response equilibrium

A set of economically-relevant decision rules

  • E.g. Strategy frequency estimation

Structural estimation

Take an economic model of how data are generated, and estimate the parameters in this model

Then:

  • Interpret the estimated parameters
  • Derive implications of the estimated parameter values

Comparison with traditional reduced-form experimental procedures

Theory says that choices \(y\mid D\) will (or will not) be different depending on treatment conditions \(D\).

Design an experiment to test whether or not \(y\mid D_1\) has the same mean, distribution, etc. as \(y\mid D_2\)

Compare treatment outcomes, e.g. with linear regression:

\[ y_{i,t}=\beta_0+\beta_1 D_{i,t}+\epsilon_{i,t},\quad H_0: \ \beta_1=0 \]

Here’s the differece

Reduced-form:

  • Model says something about \(y\mid D\)
  • Estimate/test for differences between treatments

Structural:

  • Model is a distribution \(y\mid \theta, D\)
  • Estimate \(\theta\)

We will draw a straight line through the data only if this is what the model says the data will look like!

The structural approach is very different to traditional experimental techniques

Not necessarily a need for:

  • Randomization into treatments
  • Any treatments at all
  • Designs that could falsify a theory

But you can still use data from a traditionally-designed experiment.

  • Structural estimation is a complement to the traditional experimental approach
  • But: traditional experiment designs may not be optimized for structural estimation

Structural models for economic experiments

I have a model that describes how participants will make decisions in my experiment.

I will teach you about probabilistic models, which specify a probability distribution over decisions in the experiment.

  • Likelihood \(p(y\mid\theta)\): If you tell me the model’s parameters, I can simulate data for my experiment.
  • Prior \(p(\theta)\): I have beliefs about what these parameters will look like before running the experiment

Together, I can simulate data for my experiment that is consistent with my prior beliefs about my model’s parameters

\[ p(y)= \int_{\Theta}p(y\mid\theta)p(\theta)\mathrm d\theta = E_\theta\left[p(y\mid\theta)\right] \]

Applying Bayes’ theorem to learn from data

Bayes’ theorem in general:

\[ \begin{aligned} p(A,B)&=p(A\mid B) p(B)=p(B\mid A)p(A)\\ \text{therefore: }\quad p(A\mid B)&=\frac{p(B\mid A)p(A)}{p(B)} \end{aligned} \]

Bayesian statistics: \(A=\theta\) (parameters), \(B=y\) (data):

\[ \begin{aligned} p(\theta\mid y)&=\frac{p(y\mid\theta) p(\theta)}{p(y)}\propto p(y\mid\theta)p(\theta)=p(y,\theta) \end{aligned} \]

\(p(y\mid\theta)\) is the likelihood: given \(\theta\), what will my data look like?

\(p(\theta)\) is the prior: what are my beliefs about \(\theta\) before running my experiment?

Why Bayes?

This is the right way to learn from data, according to math!

Why Bayes? More practically

The alternative is (usually) maximum likelihood.

  • Bayes often turns a difficult maximization problem into a slightly less difficult simulation problem.
  • The technology to do this simulation has improved immensely

Better handling of un-observable heterogeneity

  • Data augmentation vs. integrating the likelihood
  • Handled particularly well by Hamiltonian Monte Carlo (This is what Stan does)
  • Participants are heterogeneous!

Applying Bayes’ rule to structural models in experiments

\[ \begin{aligned} p(\theta\mid y)&=\frac{p(y\mid\theta) p(\theta)}{p(y)}\propto p(y\mid\theta)p(\theta) \end{aligned} \]

A typical procedure:

\(u(y;\theta,x)\): A (deterministic) utility function over choices \(y\) given experimental conditions \(x\) and parameters \(\theta\)

\(p(y\mid u,\theta)\): A stochastic choice rule

\(p(\theta)\): a prior for our model’s parameters

Some components of a structural model: Utility function

If present, this is usually the thing we are most interested in

\(u(y;\theta,x)\): A (deterministic) utility function over choices \(y\) given experimental conditions \(x\). For example:

Risk preferences: \[ u(y;\theta,x)=\sum_{k=1}^K p^y_k \frac{x_k^{1-r}}{1-r} \]

Time preferences:

\[ u(y;\theta,x)=\sum_{t=0}^\infty \delta^t y_t \]

The components of a structural model: A probabilistic choice rule

Converts a deterministic prediction into a probabilistic one.

  • Specifies a probability distribution over actions given utility of taking these actions
  • Necessary for constructing a likelihood
  • Behaviorally plausible

\[ \begin{aligned} \text{logit choice: } p(a\mid x,\theta)&=\frac{\exp(\lambda u_a(x,\theta))}{\sum_{j\in A}\exp(\lambda u_j(x,\theta))}\\ \text{optimal plus error: } y\mid x,\theta&\sim \arg\max_{y'\in A}u(y',x,\theta)+\epsilon,\quad \epsilon\sim N(0,\sigma^2) \end{aligned} \]

The components of a structural model: A prior

\[p(\theta)\]

Our belief about \(\theta\) before we observe our data

What are:

  • Likely values?
  • Unlikely but possible values?
  • Stupidly unlikely but still possible values?
  • Impossible values?
  • Values which pose a problem for estimation?

A formal mathematical statement of this

How can we estimate these models?

The posterior distribution \(p(\theta\mid y)\) is in general not known in closed form.

  • Fortunately, we can sample from it.
  • We then report summary statistics of these simulated draws (e.g. means, standard deviations).

The more “traditional” Bayesian approach, Gibbs sampling: needs exact conditional distributions for subsets of the parameters.

  • Great if you want to only work with linear models (I don’t)
    • Conjugate priors
  • Feasible for (mostly non-linear) structural applications, but very slow (see my job market paper (Bland 2019))
  • More user-intensive

A better way for estimating structural models

Most of the computationally difficult stuff is in handling the non-linearities, which do not work well with a Gibbs sampler.

Instead, use a probabilistic programming language that takes care of all of this!

I will teach you about Stan (Carpenter et al. 2017):

  • Free, and callable within R, Python, Matlab, Stata, etc
  • Allows us to code up models in a similar way to how we might write them down
  • Uses Hamiltonian Monte Carlo: Fast!
  • Especially well suited to handling hierarchical models
  • In-built diagnostics

Example Stan program for estimating a Normal distribution

data {
  int<lower=0> N; // number of observations in data
  vector[N] y; // data
  vector[2] prior_mu; // prior for parameter mu (mean and sd)
  real<lower=0> prior_sigma; // prior for sigma (half-cauchy)
}
parameters {
  real mu; // mean of distribution
  real<lower=0> sigma; // standard deviation of distribution
}
model {
  y ~ normal(mu, sigma); // likelihood contribution
  mu ~ normal(prior_mu[1],prior_mu[2]); // prior for mu
  sigma ~ cauchy(0.0,prior_sigma); // prior for sigma
}

What information does Stan need? Overview

Instructions on how to compute the log joint density of parameters and data:

\[ \log p(y,\theta)=\underbrace{\log p(y\mid\theta)}_\text{likelihood}+\underbrace{\log p(\theta)}_\text{prior} \]

What information does Stan need? Data block

A description of the data (any any other information you want to pass to Stan)

  • names
  • data types, e.g. int, real, vector, etc.
  • array sizes
  • bounds (optional)
data {
  int<lower=0> N; // number of observations in data
  vector[N] y; // data
  vector[2] prior_mu; // prior for parameter mu (mean and sd)
  real<lower=0> prior_sigma; // prior for sigma (half-cauchy)
}

What information does Stan need? Parameters block

  • names
  • bounds
  • parameter types
    • Must be continuous variables
    • real, vector, matrix, simplex, corr_matrix etc. allowed
    • int not allowed
parameters {
  real mu; // mean of distribution
  real<lower=0> sigma; // standard deviation of distribution
}

What information does Stan need? Model block

Instructions on how to compute the target:

\[ \log p(y,\theta)=\log p(y\mid\theta)+\log p(\theta) \]

model {
  y ~ normal(mu, sigma); // likelihood contribution
  mu ~ normal(prior_mu[1],prior_mu[2]); // prior for mu
  sigma ~ cauchy(0.0,prior_sigma); // prior for sigma
}

Alternatively:

model {
  target += normal_lpdf(y | mu, sigma); // likelihood contribution
  target += normal_lpdf(mu | prior_mu[1],prior_mu[2]); // prior for mu
  target += cauchy_lpdf(sigma | 0.0,prior_sigma); // prior for sigma
}

Optional Stan blocks

functions: Specify user-defined functions

transformed data: Data manipulations

transformed parameters: Calculate functions of parameters and data that can be used in the model block (slow-ish)

generated quantities: Calculate functions of parameters and data that cannot be used in the model block (fast)

Some other things to know about Stan

Diagnostics:

  • Only about four things that can go wrong with Hamiltonian Monte Carlo
  • All of them diagnosable (Stan does this for you)
  • Extensive documentation on them and how to fix them

Speed:

  • Compiles to C++ \(\implies\) very fast once compiled
    • Often much faster to do data manipulation in Stan than R
  • Speed improved through vectorization
  • Parallelization supported (both within- and between-chain)

Models with optimization

What are our participants maximizing?

Economic models usually involve some kind of optimization

One way to represent this is with a utility function:

\[ \max_{y\in \mathbb Y} U(y;\theta,x) \]

We can lean about \(\theta\), the parameters in \(U(\cdot;\cdot,\cdot)\), by observing choices \(y\) in different experiment conditions \(x\).

We will often have to make an assumption about the functional form of \(U(\cdot;\cdot,\cdot)\).

With an estimate of the parameters in \(U\) we can

\[ \max_{y\in \mathbb Y} U(y;\theta,x) \]

  • Interpret the estimated parameters \(\theta\)
  • Calculate economically meaningful quantities that are functions of \(\theta\)
  • Make (deterministic) predictions of what participants might do in different experiment conditions \(x\) and with different choice sets \(\mathbb Y\)

Example dataset (Harrison and Swarthout 2023)

  • 175 undergraduate participants (“House money” treatment)
  • 100 pairwise decisions each between a “Left” and “Right” lottery
    • 3 monetary prizes the same within each lottery pair (differed between each lottery pair)
    • Left and Right lotteries differed in the probability distributions over these three prizes

Notate the data as follows:

  • \(i\) indexes a participant, \(t\) indexes a decision
  • \(x_{i,t}\): A \(1\times 3\) vector of prizes for lottery pair \(t\).
  • \(q_{i,t}^L\), \(q_{i,t}^R\): \(1\times 3\) vectors of the probabilities associated with these prizes for each lottery
  • \(y_{i,t}\): lottery chosen by the participant: \(1=L\), \(0=R\)

A model to take to the data

Economic model: Expected utility theory (EUT)

Participants choose the lottery \(S\) that maximizes:

\[ E\left(u_i(X)\mid S\right), \quad S\in\{L,R\} \]

A parametric assumption: CRRA utility:

\[ u_i(x)=\frac{x^{1-r_i}}{1-r_i} \]

Some things we can do with estimates of \(r_i\): interpret \(r_i\), make (deterministic) predictions, calculate a certainty equivalent

Problem: EUT makes deterministic predictions!

Choose lottery \(L\) if and only if:

\[ U_i(L_t)=\sum_k q_{k,i,t}^L\frac{x_{k,i,t}^{1-r_i}}{1-r_i}\geq \sum_k q_{k,i,t}^R\frac{x_{k,i,t}^{1-r_i}}{1-r_i}=U_i(R_t) \]

We need models that make probabilistic predictions!

Why do we need models that make probabilistic predictions?

Participants make mistakes: need to model the mistakes

Our utility function might me mis-specified

Zero likelihood problem: One decision not consistent with maximizing \(U\) makes the likelihood zero for all parameter inputs!

Solution

Assume that choosing the left lottery reveals to us that:

\[ U_i(L_t)-U_i(R_t)+\epsilon_{i,t}\geq0 \]

Interpretation for \(\epsilon_{i,t}\):

  • The component of utility that we are not explicitly modeling
  • Random shocks to the participant’s utility
  • Errors made by the participant in assessing the utility difference \(U_i(L_t)-U_i(R_t)\)

Then we can write:

\[ p(y_{i,t}=L\mid\theta)=p(U_i(L_t)-U_i(R_t)+\epsilon_{i,t}\geq0 \mid \theta) \]

A parametric assumption

If \(\epsilon_{i,t}\) is iid type I extreme value, then we can write:

\[ \begin{aligned} p(y_{i,t}&=L\mid\theta)=\frac{\exp(\lambda U_i(L_t))}{\exp(\lambda U_i(L_t))+\exp(\lambda U_i(R_t))}\\ &=\frac{1}{1+\exp(\lambda(U_i(L_t)-U_i(R_t)))} \end{aligned} \]

New parameter: \(\lambda \geq 0\) measures choice precision

The contextual utility normalization (Wilcox 2011)

Normalize utility differences so that utility differences can be at most one

This de-couples some of the implications of the parameters \(r\) and \(\lambda\):

\[ p(y_{i,t}\mid \theta)=\frac{1}{1+\exp\left(-\lambda\frac{U_i(L_t)-U_i(R_t)}{u_i(\overline x_t)-u_i(\overline x_t)}\right)} \]

Specifying the likelihood

\[ y_{i,t}\sim \mathrm{Bernoulli}\Lambda\left(\lambda\frac{U_i(L_t)-U_i(R_t)}{u_i(\overline x_t)-u_i(\overline x_t)}\right) \]

In Stan, we can write:

y ~ bernoulli_logit(lambda*DU);

where DU is the normalized utility difference, computed earlier.

Vectorization!

This is enough information to specify the likelihood of the model

What information does Stan need? (again)

\[ \log p(y,\theta)=\log p(y\mid\theta)+\log p(\theta) \]

We have enough information to compute the likelihood \(\log p(y\mid\theta)\)

We now need to think about \(p(\theta)\), the prior.

What is a prior?

Qualitatively: what we know about our parameter(s) before we see the data

As experts (yes, you are one), you should be able to make a reasonable judgement about what are likely and unlikely realizations of a parameter

  • A daily discount factor of \(\delta=0.05\) is ridiculously small
  • A coefficient of constant relative risk-aversion of 0.5 (i.e. square-root utility) is not too surprising
  • \(\beta=1,000\) in Fehr and Schmidt (1999) is a stupidly large amount of aversion to disadvantageous inequality.

But we have to formally state this in a mathematical expression of the uncertainty we have in our parameter(s)

Step 1: picking a distributional family

Choose a family of distributions that has the right support.

E.g. \(\lambda>0\), choice precision:

  • Normal – nope: can’t have negative numbers
  • Binomial – nope: doesn’t cover \(\mathbb R_+\)
  • Log-normal – good

\(r\in \mathbb{R}\), CRRA parameter:

  • normal

Step 2: Calibrate the parameters of the distribution

\[ \begin{aligned} r&\sim N(m_r,s^2_r)\\ \log\lambda &\sim N(m_\lambda,s^2_\lambda) \end{aligned} \]

Translate our (maybe not very well-formulated) beliefs into \(m_r\), \(s_r\), \(m_\lambda\), and \(s_\lambda\),

This is usually the hard part, think about:

  • What parameter values seem Likely? Plausible? Unlikely? Just plain stupid?

  • What parameter values make plausible predictions?

  • What parameter values might pose problems for estimation?

What parameter values seem likely?

Assigning a large prior variance is not being “uninformative”!

Suppose \(\theta\sim N(0,s_\theta^2)\)

  • Likely range is \(|\theta|\leq 2\)
  • Unlikely range is \(2<|\theta|\leq 5\)
  • Stupid range is \(|\theta|>5\)

Coming up with some meaningful ranges

E.g. Holt and Laury (2002) with \(r\sim N(0.27,s_r^2)\), from Bland (2023a):

But sometimes conceptualizing a parameter is difficult

For example: \(\lambda\)

  • “choice precision”
  • What does that even mean?
  • What does a doubling of \(\lambda\) mean?
  • Units: inverse utility (hard to interpret)

Alternative approach: What do different realizations of this parameter mean about predictions in our experiment?

What are plausible and implausible predictions?

How do predictions change with \(\lambda\)

How do predictions change with \(\lambda?\)

\(L\): $30 for sure

\(R\): a 50-50 mix of $10 and $50

Calibration for \(\lambda\)

All of the interesting variation happens for \(\lambda\in(10,100)\). Use this to pin down a 95% prior credible region:

\[ \begin{aligned} \log 100 &=m_\lambda +1.96 s_\lambda\\ \log 10 &=m_\lambda -1.96 s_\lambda\\ \implies m_\lambda &\approx 3.45,\quad s_\lambda\approx 0.59 \end{aligned} \]

Doing something with the estimates

We have estimated the parameters of the economic model!

Really, we have \(S\) draws from the posterior distribution \(\{r_s,\lambda_s\}_{s=1}^S\), and reported summary statistics of these draws.

Functions of the model’s parameters may:

  • Be easier to interpret
  • Be of more interest
  • Answer different research questions

Functions of parameters are very easy to simulate!

Once we have \(\{r_s,\lambda_s\}_{s=1}^S\), it is very easy to compute:

\[ \left\{f(r_s,\lambda_s)\right\}_{s=1}^S \]

Can be done outside of Stan using extract

Done within Stan in the generated quantities block:

  • Compute functions of data and parameters
  • Not used in computing the posterior density – Fast!

Functions of the parameters for this EUT model

Given \(r\) and \(\lambda\), we can calculate a:

  • Certainty equivalent for lottery \(L\):
    • Certain amount of money \(\$c\) such that \(c\sim L\)
  • Choice probability:
    • For lotteries \(L\) and \(R\), what is the probability that \(L\) is chosen?
  • Cost of probabilistic choice (if we take the model very seriously):
    • Not necessarily a mistake – cognitive costs, mis-specified model, etc
    • Similar application to Alekseev et al. (2018)

Certainty equivalent

Lottery \(L\): a 50/50 mixture of $10 and $50

\[ \begin{aligned} \frac{c^{1-r}}{1-r}&=0.5\frac{10^{1-r}}{1-r}+0.5\frac{50^{1-r}}{1-r}\\ c&=\left(0.5\times 10^{1-r}+0.5\times 50^{1-r}\right)^\frac{1}{1-r} \end{aligned} \]

Choice probability

Lottery \(L\): a 50/50 mixture of $10 and $50

Lottery \(R\): $30 for sure

\[ \begin{aligned} p(L)&=\Lambda\left[\lambda\left(\frac{0.5\frac{10^{1-r}}{1-r}+0.5\frac{50^{1-r}}{1-r}-\frac{30^{1-r}}{1-r}}{\frac{50^{1-r}}{1-r}-\frac{10^{1-r}}{1-r}}\right)\right]\\ &=\Lambda\left[\lambda\left(\frac{0.5\times 10^{1-r}+0.5\times 50^{1-r}-30^{1-r}}{50^{1-r}-10^{1-r}}\right)\right]\\ ~\\ \Lambda(x)&=(1+\exp(-x))^{-1} \end{aligned} \]

Cost of probabilistic choice

Lottery \(L\): a 50/50 mixture of $10 and $50

Lottery \(R\): $30 for sure

Express as a difference in certainty equivalents

\[ \begin{aligned} C&^\text{no noise}-C^\text{noise}\\ &=\left((1-r)\max\{U(L),U(R)\}\right)^\frac{1}{1-r}\\ &\quad - \left[(1-r)\left(p(L)U(L)-(1-p(L))U(R)\right)\right]^\frac{1}{1-r} \end{aligned} \]

Equilibrium in games

In economics, we don’t just optimize

Equilibrium: what happens when everyone optimizes at the same time?

For this section: focus on equilibrium in games (not markets)

Computational techniques:

  • Dealing with conditions defined by a fixed point
  • Similar treatment in Bayesian and MLE approaches

Beliefs in games

In the EUT example: exogenous probabilities associated with lotteries

In games, we need:

  • A model for how players choose actions given their beliefs about opponents’ strategies
    • Nothing new here
  • A model of how players form beliefs about opponents’ strategies
    • The new part

Various kinds of models for beliefs in games

(not exhaustive)

Similar challenges to individual decision-making problems:

  • Learning: Beliefs are a function of game history

  • Introspection: Beliefs are endogenous, iterative solution

A whole new can of worms:

  • Equilibrium: Beliefs are endogenous, fixed point

The problem with equilibrium models

They have a lot of appeal, but equilibrium conditions often look like this:

\[ \sigma = F(\sigma),\quad \text{or}\quad \sigma\in F(\sigma) \]

where \(\sigma\) is a mixed strategy profile.

  • \(\sigma\) appears on both the LHS and the RHS of the equation
  • A fixed point problem
  • Typically cannot be solved with iteration (i.e. assuming a contraction)
  • Multiple solutions may exist

Big problem for us: slow to solve, and we need to solve it thousands of times!

Example experiment: Goeree, Holt, and Smith (2017)

The Volunteer’s Dilemma

At least one other player volunteers Nobody else volunteers
Volunteer V-c V-c
Not volunteer V L
  • \(V=1\), \(L=c=0.2\) constant for all treatments
  • Vary group size \(n= 2,\ 3,\ 6,\ 9,\ 12\)
  • 20 rounds played

Data

Some observations

  • Deviations from Nash prediction. On average and individually
  • Heterogeneity in choice frequencies

A model for equilibrium

Quantal response equilibrium (McKelvey and Palfrey 1995):

  • Players noisily respond to their beliefs about opponents’ mixed strategies
    • More behaviorally plausible than Nash
    • Avoids the zero likelihood problem of Nash and dominated strategies
  • Beliefs are consistent

Using the logit response specification:

\[ \sigma_{i,j}=\frac{\exp(\lambda u_{i,j}(\sigma))}{\sum_k \exp(\lambda u_{i,k}(\sigma))} \]

A simplifying assumption

Symmetry: All players volunteer with the same probability.

We will relax this later with a behavioral extension

Things we can do with a QRE model and some data

  • Estimate choice precision \(\lambda\)
  • Predict play in another treatment, e.g.
    • Different group sizes
    • Different payoff parameters
  • Compare predicted behavior to observed behavior

Some tips for solving QRE

\[ \sigma_{i,j}=\frac{\exp(\lambda u_{i,j}(\sigma))}{\sum_k \exp(\lambda u_{i,k}(\sigma))} \]

This will likely be the bulk of your computational burden. Estimation once this is done is relatively fast.

For all but the simplest problems, don’t

  • Treat it as a contraction (it probably is not one)
  • Use in-built equation solvers (you can do better)
  • Solve the system in probability levels (it is more stable in log or logit form)

Do consider using the predictor-corrector algorithm [Turocy2010]

  • Discussed in Bland and Turocy (2023)
  • Implemented in Gambit (McKelvey, McLennan, and Turocy 2022)

Fast(-ish) QRE Part 1: logs are your friend

\[ \sigma_{i,j}=\frac{\exp(\lambda u_{i,j}(\sigma))}{\sum_k \exp(\lambda u_{i,k}(\sigma))} \]

Let \(\rho_{i,j}=\log\sigma_{i,j}\)

Equilibrium conditions:

\[ \begin{aligned} 0&=\rho_{i,j+1}-\rho_{i,j}-\lambda\left[u_{i,j+1}(\rho)-u_{i,j}(\rho)\right]\quad \forall i,\ \forall j\in 1, 2, J_i-1 \end{aligned} \]

Adding-up conditions:

\[ \begin{aligned} 0&=\sum_{j=1}^{J_i}\exp(\rho_{i,j})-1 \end{aligned} \]

Stack these into a function \(H(\rho,\lambda)=0\)

Fast(-ish) QRE Part 1: logs are your friend (continued)

To estimate a model, you will need to compute the log-likelihood of your model (and combine it with a prior).

The log equilibrium mixed strategies are exactly what you need to do this!

\[ \log p(y\mid \lambda)= y^\top \rho(\lambda) \]

\[ \log p(\lambda , y)=y^\top \rho(\lambda)+\log p(\lambda) \]

where \(y_{i,j}\) is the number of times player \(i\) chose action \(j\).

Fast(-ish) QRE Part 2: Use the derivatives

\[ H(\rho,\lambda)=0 \]

The predictor-corrector algorithm uses information in \(\frac{\partial H(\rho,\lambda)}{\partial \rho^\top}\) and \(\frac{\partial H(\rho,\lambda)}{\partial \lambda}\) to make approximations of the system.

Predictor step: Starting from a known solution \((\rho,\lambda)\), use the derivatives to make a linear approximation of a new solution \((\rho',\lambda')\)

Corrector step: Use derivatives and the zero conditions to correct any errors the approximation may have introduced.

Setting up the system for the Volunteer’s dilemma

Equilibrium condition:

\[ 0=\rho_V-\rho_N-\lambda\left[V-c-V(1-\exp(\rho_N)^{n-1})-L\exp(\rho_N)^{n-1}\right] \]

Adding-up condition:

\[ 0=\exp(\rho_V)+\exp(\rho_N)-1 \]

So:

\[ H(\rho,\lambda)=\begin{pmatrix} \rho_V-\rho_N-\lambda\left[V-c-V(1-\exp(\rho_N)^{n-1})-L\exp(\rho_N)^{n-1}\right]\\ \exp(\rho_V)+\exp(\rho_N)-1 \end{pmatrix} \]

An even faster way to solve this

Make the problem 1-dimesional. Let \(\ell = \log (\sigma_V)-\log(1-\sigma_V)\)

\[ H(\ell,\lambda)=\ell-\lambda\left[V-c-V(1-\Lambda(-\ell)^{n-1})-L\Lambda(-\ell)^{n-1}\right] \] \[ \begin{aligned} \frac{\partial H(\ell,\lambda)}{\partial \ell} &=1+\lambda \Lambda'(\ell)(V-L)(n-1)\Lambda(-\ell)^{n-2}\\ ~\\ \text{where }\Lambda(x)&=(1+\exp(-x))^{-1}\\ \Lambda'(x)&=\Lambda(x)(1-\Lambda(x))=\Lambda(x)\Lambda(-x) \end{aligned} \]

Constant-\(\lambda\) corrector steps

\[ \ell^{t+1}=\ell^t-\frac{H(\ell^t,\lambda)}{\frac{\partial H(\ell^t,\lambda)}{\partial \ell}} \]

Keep iterating until \(|\ell^{t+1}-\ell^t|<\epsilon\)

Predictions and data

Hierarchical models

Participants are heterogeneous!

Experimenter-induced heterogeneity: We may have assigned players different roles in a game.

  • We control this kind of heterogeneity

Observable participant characteristics:

  • E.g. demographics collected in a survey

Unobservable participant characteristics:

  • We don’t observe these things, but we can structurally estimate them
  • E.g. risk, time, other-regarding preferences

Here we will worry about the third kind

Why you should care about heterogeneity

Heterogeneity might be interesting in itself. Estimating a model assuming no heterogeneity denies you this information.

Pooled models will overstate the confidence you should have in your estimates: If \(N\) participants make \(T\) decisions each, you don’t have \(N\times T\) independent observations.

Heterogeneity bias. Even if you don’t care about heterogeneity, assuming participants are homogeneous can produce misleading results.

  • Nuisance parameters
  • See Wilcox (2006) for an example using learning models

But individual-level estimation can also be a problem

Solution??? Estimate one model per participant

  • Might not have enough observations to do this meaningfully
  • Not a clear way to organize the data as a whole
  • Not clear what we would be doing if there is an equilibrium condition

Hierarchical models: Assume that participants are random draws from a population, estimate the parameters governing the population distribution.

A basic hierarchical model

\(\theta_i\): parameters describing participant \(i\)’s behavior

  • \(r_i\) and \(\lambda_i\) in the EUT model

\(\Theta\): parameters describing the distribution of \(\theta_i\) in the population

\[ \theta_i \sim iid \mathcal{F}(\Theta) \]

Almost all applications in the literature assume a multivariate normal specification:

\[ \theta_i\sim iid N(\mu,\Sigma) \]

What can we do with hierarchical models?

\[ \theta_i\sim iid N(\mu,\Sigma) \]

  • Model heterogeneity that we suspect is present
  • Quantify the extent of this heterogeneity (i.e. interpret \(\Sigma\))
  • Get participant-specific estimates of \(\theta_i\) that leverage the entire dataset
  • Calculate economically meaningful quantities that are functions of the individual-level parameters and/or population-level parameters.

The math behind hierarchical models

Suppose we want to estimate the population-level parameters \(\mu\) and \(\Sigma\)

\[ \begin{aligned} p(\mu,\Sigma\mid y)&\propto p(y\mid \mu,\Sigma)\ p(\mu,\Sigma) \\ &=\int p(y,\theta\mid \mu,\Sigma)\mathrm d\theta\ p(\mu,\Sigma)\\ &=\int p(y\mid \theta,\mu,\Sigma)p(\theta\mid \mu,\Sigma)\mathrm d\theta \ p(\mu,\Sigma)\\ &=\int p(y\mid \theta)p(\theta\mid \mu,\Sigma)\mathrm d\theta \ p(\mu,\Sigma) \end{aligned} \]

  • Similar to MLE approach – integrate the likelihood (with simulation)

However modern Bayesian techniques (especially HMC) do better when we use data augmentation …

Data augmentation in hierarchical models

Jointly estimate the individual-level and population-level parameters

\[ \begin{aligned} p(\theta,\mu,\Sigma\mid y)&\propto p(y\mid \theta,\mu,\Sigma)\ p(\theta,\mu,\Sigma)\\ &=p(y\mid \theta)\ p(\theta\mid \mu,\Sigma)\ p(\mu,\Sigma) \end{aligned} \]

\(p(y\mid \theta)\): individual likelihood contributions

\(p(\theta\mid \mu,\Sigma)\): “prior” for individual-level parameters

  • We don’t need to specify this, as it is determined by \((\mu,\Sigma)\)

\(p(\mu,\Sigma)\): prior for population-level parameters

  • This is the prior we need to specify.

Data augmentation in Stan

parameters {
  matrix[k,n] theta;
  vector[k] mu;
  corr_matrix[k] Omega;
  vector<lower=0>[k] Tau;
}

model {
  // put some code here that adds the likelihood to the target
  
  matrix[k,k] Sigma = quad_form_diag(Omega, Tau);
  // hierarchical structure ("prior" for theta)
  theta ~ multivariate_normal(mu,Sigma);
  // priors
  Omega ~ lkj_corr(4.0); // (prior for Omega)
  Tau ~ cauchy(0.0,1.0); // (prior for Tau)
}

Example: Back to the Volunteer’s Dilemma

Warm glow volunteering: Participants receive bonus utility \(\theta_i\) from volunteering

Duplicate aversion: Participants suffer loss \(\theta_i\) if they volunteer unnecessarily

In both cases, assume that:

\[ \theta_i \sim iid\ \mathrm{Truncated\ Normal}(\mu,\tau^2,(\mu-\tau,\mu+\tau)) \]

  • Goeree, Holt, and Smith (2017) assume a discretized version of this
  • Allowing much more spread than \(\mu \pm \tau\) results in dividing by something close to zero

How these extensions affect utility

Let \(\bar\sigma_V =\) average probability that a player volunteers

Warm glow:

\[ u_V(\bar\sigma_V,\theta_i)=V-c+\theta_i \]

Duplicate aversion: \[ u_V(\bar\sigma_V,\theta_i)=V-c-\theta_i\left(1-(1-\bar\sigma_V)^{n-1}\right) \]

Utility of not volunteering is unchanged:

\[ u_N(\bar\sigma_V,\theta_i)=V\left(1-(1-\bar\sigma_V)^{n-1}\right)+L(1-\bar\sigma_V)^{n-1} \]

A complication

The equilibrium condition! We now have a Bayesian game.

\[ \begin{aligned} \bar \sigma_V&=E_\theta\left[\frac{\exp(\lambda u_V(\bar\sigma_V,\theta))}{\exp(\lambda u_V(\bar\sigma_V,\theta))+\exp(\lambda u_N(\bar\sigma_V,\theta))}\right]\\ &=E_\theta\left[\Lambda\left(\lambda\left(u_V(\bar\sigma_V,\theta)-u_N(\bar\sigma_V,\theta)\right)\right)\right] \end{aligned} \]

We can solve this approximately with Monte Carlo integration:

\[ \bar \sigma_V\approx \frac1S\sum_{s=1}^S\Lambda\left(\lambda\left(u_V(\bar\sigma_V,\theta_s)-u_N(\bar\sigma_V,\theta_s)\right)\right) \]

Why this works: I only care about the probability my opponents volunteer, not their preferences.

Setting up a stable system to solve

Let \(\bar l = \log(\bar\sigma_V)-\log(1-\bar\sigma_V)\)

\[ \begin{aligned} 0=H(\bar\ell,\lambda)&=\bar\ell-\log\left(\frac1S\sum_{s=1}^S\Lambda\left(\lambda\left(u_V(\bar\sigma_V,\theta_s)-u_N(\bar\sigma_V,\theta_s)\right)\right)\right)\\ &\quad \quad+\log\left(\frac1S\sum_{s=1}^S\left[1-\Lambda\left(\lambda\left(u_V(\bar\sigma_V,\theta_s)-u_N(\bar\sigma_V,\theta_s)\right)\right)\right]\right) \end{aligned} \]

Then iterate on:

\[ \bar\ell^{t+1}=\bar\ell^t-\frac{H(\bar\ell^t,\lambda)}{\frac{\partial H(\bar\ell^t,\lambda)}{\partial \bar\ell}} \]

Can we do anything with all of the augmented data?

Recall, we drew from the posterior:

\[ \theta,\lambda ,\mu,\tau \mid y \]

Up to this point, we have interpreted the population parameters \(\lambda\), \(\mu\), and \(\tau\), and some predictions implied by them.

We also have the \(\theta\)s, which are the augmented data.

Interpretation of the augmented data

Consider the draws for just one participant’s parameter \(\theta_i\).

These are draws from \(\theta_i\mid y\)

  • Conditioning on both \(y_i\) and \(y_{-i}\)

What do all of the data tell us about \(\theta_i\)?

  • \(y_i\) tells us something about \(\theta_i\) because \(i\) made these decisions
  • \(y_{-i}\) also tells us something:
    • What are appropriate values for \(\mu\) and \(\tau\)?
    • Knowing things about the population is useful in knowing something about an individual participant

Warm glow individual-level parameters

Duplicate aversion individual-level parameters

But now we have three models!

We estimated three QRE models

  1. Homogeneous
  2. Warm glow volunteering
  3. Duplicate aversion

Which one should we take the most seriously?

As with other things, we treat this probabilistically.

Posterior probability of a model

\[ p(A\mid B)\propto p(B\mid A)p(A) \]

Re-label some parts of Bayes’ rule again:

\[ p(\mathrm{model}\mid y)\propto p(y\mid \mathrm{model})p(\mathrm{model}) \]

\(p(y\mid \mathrm{model})\): The “marginal likelihood” from:

\[ p(\theta\mid y, \mathrm{model})=\frac{p(y\mid \theta,\mathrm{model})p(\theta\mid \mathrm{model})}{p(y\mid \mathrm{model})} \]

When we were just estimating one model, we left out “\(\mathrm{model}\)” in our notation, but it is implicitly there.

Can be done in R using the bridgesampling library

prior: each model is equally likely

Discrete vs. continuous heterogeneity

Hierarchical models: heterogeneous parameters are continuous random variables

Sometimes we also need to add discrete heterogeneity to our models

  • Expected utility theory or prospect theory
  • Broad or narrow bracketing
  • Level-\(k\) thinking (\(k\) is discrete)
  • Strategies used in an indefinitely repeated game

Discrete heterogeneity and types

Suppose we have types indexed by \(\tau\).

Each type specifies a different likelihood function:

\[ p(y\mid \theta,\tau) \]

“What would the data look like if it was generated by only type \(\tau\)?”

Mixing probabilities

Each type \(\tau\) has a mixing probability \(\psi_\tau\)

  • The probability that a chunk of data is generated by type \(\tau\)
    • Participants, e.g. Conte, Hey, and Moffatt (2011)
    • Individual decisions, e.g. Harrison and Rutström (2009)

These are often the quantities we are most interested in!

The fraction of participants who:

  • Use the EUT model
  • Are selfish
  • Play “Always defect” in an indefinitely repeated Prisoner’s Dilemma
  • Bracket decisions narrowly

A Stan-specific problem

Stan can only deal with continuous parameters, so we can’t augment the data by \(\tau\)

Instead, to compute the likelihood, we integrate it out:

\[ p(y\mid\theta)=\sum_{\tau}\psi_\tau p(y\mid \theta,\tau)=E_\tau[p(y\mid \tau,\theta)] \]

See the appendix of the working paper version of Bland (2020) for an example of the the data-augmentation approach using a Gibbs sampler: https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3324606

More on integrating out types

We need to add the log likelihood to the target:

\[ \begin{aligned} \log p(y\mid\theta)&=\log\left(\sum_{\tau}\psi_\tau p(y\mid \theta,\tau)\right)\\ &=\log\left(\sum_\tau\psi_\tau\exp\left(\log p(y\mid\theta,\tau)\right) \right) \\ &=\log\left(\sum_\tau\exp\left(\log \psi_\tau+ \log p(y\mid\theta,\tau)\right) \right) \end{aligned} \]

now we can use log_sum_exp()

Example: Dal Bó and Fréchette (2011)

Indefinitely repeated Prisoner’s Dilemma

\(C\) \(D\)
\(C\) \(R\), \(R\) \(12\), \(50\)
\(D\) \(50\), \(12\) \(25\), \(25\)

Treatments:

  • Discount factor \(\delta\in\{\frac12,\ \frac34\}\)
  • Payoff from cooperating: \(R\in\{32,\ 40,\ 48\}\)

Data used: Games that started after more than 110 interactions.

Strategy frequency estimation

Assume that every player is using exactly one of a given list of strategies:

  1. Always Defect (AD)
  2. Always Cooperate (AC)
  3. Grim Trigger (G), defect for ever once one person has defected
  4. Tit for Tat (TFT)
  5. Win Stay Lose Shit (WSLS)
  6. Tit for two tats (T2)

Estimate the fraction of participants who use each strategy

Some notation

  • \(y_{i,\tau} =\) the number of times participant \(i\) chose consistently with strategy \(\tau\)
  • \(n_{i} =\) the total number of decisions participant \(i\) made

The (usual) problem with likelihoods

Problem: All of these strategies are deterministic

Solution: Add in a tremble \(\gamma\in(0,\ 0.5)\)

\[ p(y_{i,\tau}\mid \gamma, n_i,\tau)= (1-\gamma)^{y_{i,\tau}}\gamma^{n_i-y_{i,\tau}} \]

Implementation

\[ \begin{aligned} \psi&\sim\mathrm{Dirichlet}(1,1,1,1,1,1)\\ \gamma&\sim\mathrm{Truncated\ Beta}(1,1,(0,0.5)) \end{aligned} \]

Stan file: SFEMhomogeneous.stan

  • Note the use of log_sum_exp()

R code: SFEM.R

Results in graph form

(This hides any expression of uncertainty in the estimates)

An extension

Previous specification:

  • Same likelihood as Dal Bó and Fréchette (2011)
  • Just added priors and estimated using Bayesian techniques

But participants could be heterogeneous

  • They use different strategies
    • The model already accounts for this
  • They could tremble with different probabilities
    • We assumed that \(\gamma\) was homogeneous within a treatment

Heterogeneous trembles – why should we care?

With SFEM, the goal is to estimate the mixing probabilities \(\psi\)

\(\gamma\) is a nuisance parameter:

  • We don’t care directly about estimating it
  • But we have to estimate it alongside \(\psi\)

Heterogeneity bias: If we assume a parameter is homogeneous when it isn’t, we can make misleading conclusions

E.g. Wilcox (2006):

  • “… in the presence of parameter heterogeneity, pooled estimation can produce a severe bias that tends to unduly favor reinforcement learning relative to belief learning.” (from the abstract)
  • Main culprit here is choice precision: a nuisance parameter

A 1-parameter extension for heterogeneous trembles

\[ \begin{aligned} \gamma_i&=\frac12\Phi(\mu+z_i\sigma),\quad z_i\sim N(0,1) \end{aligned} \]

  • \(\Phi(\cdot)\): standard normal cdf
  • Transformation ensures that \(\gamma_i\in(0,0.5)\)

Implementation

Stan file: SFEMheterogeneous.stan

R file: SFEM.R

Note the options used in calling Stan:

  • iter = 10000 (default \(=\) 2,000)
  • adapt_delta = 0.9999 (default \(=\) 0.8)

Conclusion

Big picture

I have a model (or models) and I want to:

  • Estimate and comment on the parameters
  • Comment on transformations of the parameters
  • Comment on the importance of each model
  • Assign a measure of uncertainty to all of the above

We have a framework for doing this

Bayesian statistics

Applying Bayes’ rule to quantify posterior uncertainty in:

  • Our model’s parameters

\[ p(\theta\mid y)\propto p(y\mid \theta) p(\theta) \]

  • Assigning probabilities to models

\[ p(M\mid y)\propto p(y\mid M) p(M) \]

The structural approach

Estimate the parameters in the model

  • Interpret the parameters
  • Interpret implications of the parameters, e.g.:
    • Predicted actions
    • Certainty equivalents

Compared to reduced-form:

  • Compare differences in treatments,
  • Draw a straight line through the data, interpret the slope

Heterogeneity

Our participants are heterogeneous, and we should model this!

Bayesian techniques do this well

Some useful tools:

  • Hierarchical models: Continuous types
    • Data augmentation
  • Mixture models: Discrete types
    • Integrate the likelihood

Heterogeneity in a parameter could be important, even if you don’t care about that parameter!

The econometrics of games

New concept compared to individual choice: equilibrium

Can be a fixed point problem

  • Difficult and slow to solve
  • Some tricks to help
    • compute in logs (stability)
    • predictor-corrector (using the derivatives)

So when should I think about structural?

Before running an experiment!

  • What might my data look like?
  • Can I modify my experiment to better answer my research question?
  • Will my experiment adequately estimate the models/quantities that I want it to?

After the experiment

  • To complement a traditional analysis (comparing treatments)
  • Estimate economically meaningful quantities

What are some things I should be thinking about when estimating structural models?

  • How will this help answer my research question?
    • Economically meaningful quantities
    • Parameters/quantities that we can interpret
  • What are the underlying assumptions of the model(s) I take to the data?
  • How am I accounting for heterogeneity?
    • Heterogeneity that I care about
    • Heterogeneity that I don’t care about but might affect my estimates

What are some things to think about when doing Bayesian work?

  • What do my priors say about:
    • Reasonable and unreasonable parameter values?
    • The data I might collect?
    • Economically meaningful quantities
    • The performance of my estimator?
  • Data augmentation
    • Good for models with heterogeneity
    • In Stan: only continuous variables – integrate the likelihood for discrete heterogeneity

Placating the frequentists

Correspondence with the guest editor for the JESA special issue on “Statistical Issues for Experimental Economists”, December 2019

… However, we feel that a Bayesian approach here is not appropriate for the Special Issue, particularly given the econometric sophistication of the readership and the difficulty of your problem. Your paper goes straight into a Bayesian analysis without stating why the Bayesian approach is preferable to the classical approach.

Lessons learned:

  • We still have to justify why we are not using frequentist techniques (although this is getting better)
  • JESA readers lack “econometric sophisticiation”?

For the record, this problem was much easier to implement with Bayes

Placating the frequentists

Stress the practical side of Bayesian estimation: it can turn a difficult maximization problem into a slightly less difficult simulation problem

  • Especially for hierarchical models
  • Expressions of uncertainty
    • Bayesian – part of the simulation
    • Frequentist – bootstrap or delta method
  • Show them what you can do with Bayes

Show that you have thought about your priors.

  • Have a good answer for why you chose them.
  • Maybe do a prior sensitivity analysis

Last resort: capitulate. E.g. Bland (2020)

Things not covered today but worth a look

Experiment design

  • With the goal of estimating a structural model
  • Using structural estimates
  • E.g. Bland (2023b)

Model selection using cross-validation

  • Not specific to Bayes
  • Application to QRE here: Bland (2022)

Where are some datasets I can use to practice?

Experimental economics has really good data-sharing norms! If a paper is published, chances are you can get the data.
